Population numbers are given in millions and areas are given in square kilometers. The three different kinds of populations refer to different ways of describing what is included in a city. The feature population is a measurement from the UN (2018) that tries to consistently define the region of a city. More information is available in the U.N.’s World Urbanization Prospectus, which is available here. The other three measurements refer to:

  • city: city proper, defined by local administrative boundaries
  • metro: according to UNICEF, the Metro Region is an area “comprising the urban area as a whole and its primary commuter areas… In addition to the city proper, a metropolitan area includes both the surrounding territory with urban levels of residential density and some additional lower-density areas that are adjacent to and linked to the city.” See UNICEF for more information.
  • urban: an area that consists of a “continuously built up land mass of urban development that is within a labor market (metropolitan area or metropolitan region) and contains no rural land”.

Several of the questions in this and the following notebooks concern the analysis of the relationship between these various definitions.

Scatterplot

In the code below, write the code to produce a scatter plot with population on the x-axis and the city population on the y-axis. I have set warning=FALSE because there are some missing data values and it will be helpful to turn off the warnings about these data rows.

cities |>
  ggplot() +
    geom_point(aes(x = population, y = city_pop))

Now, in the code region below, produce a scatter plot with population on the x-axis and metro population on the y-axis.

cities |>
  ggplot() +
    geom_point(aes(x = population, y = metro_pop))

Which of the two regional populations (metro or city) seem to more closely relate to the U.N.’s definition of a cities population (e.g., the population feature). Answer: The metropolitan population is much closer to the UN definition than the city population feature

Text Plot

Produce a plot with population on the x-axis and metro population on the y-axis and label each point with the city name.

cities |>
  ggplot() +
    geom_text(aes(x = population, y = metro_pop, label = city))

What two cities seem to have the largest (absolute) discrepancy between their UN population and the metro population? Answer: Jakarta and Seoul seem to stand out the most (their metro populations are much larger than the official UN population numbers).

Produce a plot with a text geometry where longitude (lon) is on the x-axis, latitude is on the y-axis (lat), and the labels are given by the city names (name).

cities |>
  ggplot() +
    geom_text(aes(x = lon, y = lat, label = name))

This should roughly resemble a map of the world. In the code below, produce a modified version of this plot, replacing the text layer with two layers: a text repel layer and well as a point layer.

cities |>
  ggplot() +
    geom_text_repel(aes(x = lon, y = lat, label = name)) +
    geom_point(aes(x = lon, y = lat))

Which of these two plots do you find easier to read, and why? (Note, there is no clear correct answer here). Answer: I slightly prefer the second, but it would be better to, perhaps, show only a subset of the labels. We will see how to do this soon!

hans |>
  ggplot() +
    geom_point(aes(x = gdp, y = life_exp))
